Remember HR 1 or S 1, the so-called “For the People Act?” We’ve done several episodes about on it on Heritage Explains where we’ve talked about how, if passed, it would fundamentally change America by letting DC control our elections instead of the states. Since our last episode, Democrat Sen. Joe Manchin from West Virginia actually wrote an op-ed digging his heels in, and rejected H.R. 1/S. 1. Or did he? Have you heard of H.R. 4? It's been described as the "backdoor" to the "For the People Act." The problem is that it might be worse. This week, we discuss the differences between H.R. 1 and H.R. 4, the state of play, and all that is at stake.

Let’s imagine you’re on a road trip. 

But you’re not paying attention to how much gas you’re using. Before you know it, you’re stuck on the side of the road and have to call a tow truck. 

Thanks to decades of wasteful Washington spending, that’s where we’re at in America with our national debt. Join Senator Rick Scott and The Heritage Foundation for a new series that highlights how we can work together to put America back on a fiscally responsible path forward.

Heritage Foundation president Kay C. James calls out the left’s latest attempt to weaken election security and manipulate elections so that they can gain power and implement their radical agenda. After the widely unpopular and misnamed “For the People Act” failed in the U.S. Senate, the left has shifted its focus to H.R. 4, euphemistically titled “The John Lewis Voting Rights Advancement Act.” 

Although the bill is named after a civil rights icon, passage of the legislation would result in making it easier for cheaters to cheat in elections and would cancel the votes of eligible, law-abiding voters of all races and backgrounds.

#elections #election #electionintegrity #vote #votingrights #johnlewis #johnlewisvotingrightsact
